draw(A--O--B,linewidth(0.7));
label("$O$",O,SE);
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,NW);
[/asy]

Draw the radii of the circle to the vertices of the hexagon.  This divides the hexagon into 6 equilateral triangles, each with side length 2.  The area of one of these triangles is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \cdot 2^2 = \sqrt{3}$, so the area of the hexagon is $6 \cdot \sqrt{3} = \boxed{6\sqrt{3}}$ square units.

Solution:
Let $O$ be the center of the circle, and let $A,$ $B,$ $C,$ $D,$ $E,$ and $F$ be the vertices of the hexagon.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, O;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(0);
B = dir(60);
C = dir(120);
D = dir(180);
E = dir(240);
F = dir(300);

draw(Circle(O,2));
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--cycle);

label("$A$", A, dir(0));
label("$B$", B, dir(60));
label("$C$", C, dir(120));
label("$D$", D, dir(180));
label("$E$", E, dir(240));
label("$F$", F, dir(300));
label("$O$", O, NE);
[/asy]

Since the hexagon is regular, all of its interior angles are $120^\circ.$  Therefore, $\angle AOC = 2 \cdot 120^\circ = 240^\circ,$ so $\triangle AOC$ is an isosceles triangle with $AO = CO = 2$ and $\angle AOC = 240^\circ.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, C, O;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(0);
C = dir(120);

draw(Circle(O,2));
draw(A--O--C--cycle);

label("$A$", A, dir(0));
label("$C$", C, dir(120));
label("$O$", O, NE);
[/asy]

Then triangle $AOC$ is equilateral with side length 2, so its area is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \cdot 2^2 = \sqrt{3}.$  The area of the hexagon is six times the area of $\triangle AOC,$ so the area of the hexagon is $6 \sqrt{3} = \boxed{6 \sqrt{3}}.$
